{{表記揺れ案内|表記1=豊鹿嶋神社|表記2=豊鹿島神社|表記3=|議論ページ=}} {{Shrine | Name = Toyokashima Shrine | image = [[File:豊鹿嶋神社正面より.jpg|300px]] | location = {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Higashiyamato, Tokyo|ja|東大和市|12=draft|12=draft}} Imokubo 1-2067<ref name="cho"/> | coordinates = {{Coord|35|45|28.5|N|139|24|46.2|E|type:landmark_region:JP-13}} | deity = {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武御加豆智命|12=draft|12=draft}} | Status = {{ill|Gōsha (Shinto)|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} | Established = 1466 | Festival = | Map = Japan Tokyo }}
'''Toyokashima Shrine''' (豊鹿嶋神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Higashiyamato, Tokyo|ja|東大和市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tokyo. The enshrined deity is {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武御加豆智命|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="cho">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://www.tokyo-jinjacho.or.jp/kitatama/higashiyamato/5762/|title=豊鹿嶋神社|publisher={{ill|Tokyo Association of Shinto Shrines|ja|東京都神社庁|12=draft|12=draft}}|accessdate=2019-09-27}}</ref>. The shrine's '''main hall (honden)''', built in 1466 during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, is the oldest existing {{ill|Shinto shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|12=draft|12=draft}} in Tokyo<ref name="cho"/>.
== History ==
According to the shrine tradition, in '''707 CE''' ({{ill|Keiun|ja|慶雲|12=draft|12=draft}} 4), a '''demon god''' that arrived in {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|12=draft|12=draft}} was pacified at '''Hitachi Peak''', and the shrine was founded by the '''fourth princess of {{ill|Emperor Tenji|ja|天智天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}''' and {{ill|Soga no Kurayamada no Ishikawa no Maro|ja|蘇我倉山田石川麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="book">{{Cite book |ja|author={{ill|Ueda Mōshin|ja|植田孟縉|12=draft|12=draft}}|year=1993|title=武蔵名勝図会 |page= |publisher=慶友社|isbn=4874490808}}</ref>. Since then, it has been protected by the residents of the '''Imokubo area''' as their guardian shrine<ref name="cho"/>.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was granted '''13 koku''' of shrine land ({{ill|Sharyō|ja|社領|12=draft|12=draft}})<ref name="city">{{Cite web|ja|title=11 豊鹿島神社|url=https://www.city.higashiyamato.lg.jp/index.cfm/34,5862,360,622,html|publisher={{ill|Higashiyamato City|ja|東大和市|12=draft|12=draft}}|accessdate=2019-09-27}}</ref>.
In '''1993''' ({{ill|Heisei era|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}} 5), during a major '''restoration of the haiden''' (worship hall), a '''tōsatsu (ridge plaque)''' dated to '''1466''' ({{ill|Bunshō|ja|文正|12=draft|12=draft}} 1) was discovered, confirming the shrine's founding year, as previously recorded in the '''Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō''' ({{sfn|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿}}). Additionally, five other '''tōsatsu''' were found, revealing that the haiden before the restoration was constructed in '''1858''' ({{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|12=draft|12=draft}} 5)<ref name="book"/>.
== Cultural Properties ==
=== Tokyo Designated Tangible Cultural Property (Architecture) ===
* '''Toyokashima Shrine Honden (Main Hall), 1 building''' - designated as a Tokyo Important Cultural Property on '''November 21, 1964''' (Showa 39), reclassified on '''July 1, 1976'''<ref name="to">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://bunkazai.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/jp/search_detail.html?page=1&id=205|title=豊鹿島神社本殿|website=Tokyo Cultural Property Database|publisher={{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Board of Education|ja|東京都教育委員会|12=draft|12=draft}}|accessdate=2019-09-28}}</ref> : The shrine features a '''single-bay nagare-zukuri''' ({{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft|12=draft}}) main hall with '''kokera-buki (wooden shingles)''' and a '''box ridge'''. The dimensions are '''170.7 cm in width''', with the '''shrine core (moya)''' having a '''depth of 152.4 cm''', and the '''front eaves (kōhai)''' extending '''140.4 cm'''<ref name="to"/>. The structure is currently housed within a '''protective covering hall''' ({{ill|Oudou|ja|覆堂|12=draft|12=draft}}) to shield it from the elements, making it inaccessible for direct viewing<ref name="cho"/>. Previously, the '''tōsatsu''' stored inside the main hall was believed to indicate the construction year as '''1550''' ({{ill|Tenbun|ja|天文|12=draft|12=draft}} 19), but a '''new tōsatsu''' discovered during the '''1992–1994 dismantling repairs''' confirmed the construction date as '''1466''' (Bunshō 1), with records of a '''master carpenter named Jirōsaburō Chikayoshi'''. The roof was also originally made of '''thick wooden planks (atsuita-buki)'''<ref name="to"/>.
=== Higashiyamato City Designated Cultural Property (Municipal Treasure) ===
* '''Toyokashima Shrine Wooden Komainu (Guardian Lion-Dogs)''' - designated on '''March 1, 1983''' (Showa 58)<ref name="bunka">{{Cite web|ja|title=東大和市の文化財|url=https://www.city.higashiyamato.lg.jp/index.cfm/34,2279,359,html|publisher={{ill|Higashiyamato City|ja|東大和市|12=draft|12=draft}}|accessdate=2019-09-28}}</ref> : These wooden komainu are believed to have been crafted '''during the same period as the honden'''<ref name="bunka"/>.
* '''Toyokashima Shrine Shishigashira (Lion Head)''' - designated on '''March 1, 1983'''<ref name="bunka"/> : This lion head, likely from the '''late Edo period''', was used in '''lion dances''' ({{ill|Shishimai|ja|獅子舞|12=draft|12=draft}}) that were formerly performed at the shrine<ref name="bunka"/>.
